Task 1: Boosting the economy by incentivizing self-employment¶

Assume the biggest priority of the local government in 2018 is to increase per-capita income. To do so, the officials plan to adopt a strategy for incentivizing self-employment through a series of campaigns, educational programs, and dedicated funds.

Since it is unethical and impossible in this setting to run a controlled experiment involving citizens (e.g., fire employees and force them to self-employ), the officials have asked you, the data scientist, to establish the effect of self-employment on the economy, relying on observational data.

A) You will be working with the full US 2015 census dataset (acs2015_county_data.csv, available at https://www.kaggle.com/muonneutrino/us-census-demographic-data#acs2015_county_data.csv). Using suitable methods, determine and quantify the dependency between the percentage of self-employed citizens and per capita income across all 3,212 US counties. Do citizens in counties that have a higher percentage of self-employed people earn more per capita?

B) The pilot program will involve all counties within a limited set of three US states. Set A includes Wisconsin, Tennessee, and Minnesota. Quantify the dependency of per-capita income on self-employment rates across all the counties in set A.

C) In which state within set A is the observed effect of self-employment on per-capita income the strongest?

D) Set B includes New Jersey, Kansas, and Rhode Island. Repeat the analysis from steps B and C above, but now for set B. In which of the two sets A and B (if any) would you recommend incentivizing self-employment? Explain your reasoning.

Hint: It is useful to add a notion of confidence to your results and explore the data visually. You are allowed to use the SciPy library.

# return df of specified states
def select_states(select_only):
    res_states = df_america[df_america["State"].str.contains("|".join(select_only))]
    return res_states

def draw_scatter_for_single_states(df, ax, title,
                                x_data, y_data, color="blue", regColor="red", opacity=0.8, state="all"):
    # add linear regression
    x = df[x_data]
    y = df[y_data]
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)
    ax.plot(x, slope*x+intercept, linestyle='solid', lw=3, c=regColor, label='regr. fit '+ state)

    # add regresstion data
    corr, p_val = stats.spearmanr(x, y)
    ax.scatter(x=df["SelfEmployed"], y=df["IncomePerCap"], alpha=opacity, edgecolors=(0, 0, 0), c=color, label=state)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xlabel(x_data)
    ax.set_ylabel(y_data)

    dollar_format = '${x:,.0f}'
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mtick.StrMethodFormatter(dollar_format)) 
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mtick.PercentFormatter(decimals=0)) 
    
    ax.legend()
    return (slope, intercept, [corr, p_val])

def draw_scatter_states_(df, states, colors=["red", "gold", "green"], 
                        x_data="SelfEmployed", y_data="IncomePerCap"):
    data = {}
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(states), 1, figsize=(15, 12))
    for idx in range(0, len(states)):
        tmp_df = df_america[df_america["State"] == states[idx]]
        draw_all = draw_scatter_for_single_states(df, ax[idx], title="Self Emplyoment",
                                            x_data=x_data, y_data=y_data,
                                            color="lightgrey", regColor="lightgrey", opacity=0.2)
        single_state_vals = draw_scatter_for_single_states(tmp_df, ax[idx], title="Self Emplyoment", 
                                            x_data=x_data, y_data=y_data, 
                                            color=colors[idx%len(colors)], regColor=colors[idx%len(colors)],
                                            opacity=1, state=states[idx])
        data[states[idx]] = single_state_vals
    plt.tight_layout()
    return data

def read_process_file():
    '''
        Reads the files and converts the cateotry features to dummy variables
        Returns:
           - features datasets
           - class dataset
    '''
    zip_path = ZipFile(data_folder + 'austin-animal-center-shelter-intakes-and-outcomes.zip')
    df_animals = pd.read_csv(zip_path.open('aac_intakes_outcomes.csv'))

    animal_features = ['animal_type','intake_year','intake_condition',
                           'intake_number','intake_type', 'sex_upon_intake',
                           'age_upon_intake_(years)','time_in_shelter_days',
                           'sex_upon_outcome','age_upon_outcome_(years)']

    animal_y = ['outcome_type']

    #Extracting only the features that are needed for the task
    df_animals_features = df_animals[animal_features]
    df_animals_class = df_animals[animal_y]

    #Changing the categorical features into dummie variables with zeros and ones
    animals_training = pd.get_dummies(df_animals_features[animal_features])
    adopted = pd.get_dummies(df_animals_class)

    #Extracting the class value
    animals_adopted = adopted['outcome_type_Adoption']
    return animals_adopted, animals_training

# Splits the dataset into a two subsets of a preset ratio
def split_to_train_and_test_set(x, y, ratio, seed=1):
    # sets a seed for the split
    np.random.seed(seed)
    
    # generate random indices
    num_row = len(y)
    indices = np.random.permutation(num_row)
    index_split = int(np.floor(ratio * num_row))
    index_tr = indices[: index_split]
    index_te = indices[index_split:]
    
    # create split
    x_tr = x[index_tr]
    x_te = x[index_te]
    y_tr = y[index_tr]
    y_te = y[index_te]
    return x_tr, x_te, y_tr, y_te

def build_confusion_matrix(predicted, true_values, class_to_choose = 'adopted'):
    '''
    Makes the confusion matrix and manually calculates the values for
    accuracy, precision, recall and f1 score

    'choose' chooses the class with which accuracy, precision,
    recall and f1_score is calculated    
    '''
    
    TP = np.sum(np.logical_and(predicted == 1, true_values == 1))
    TN = np.sum(np.logical_and(predicted == 0, true_values == 0))
    FP = np.sum(np.logical_and(predicted == 1, true_values == 0))
    FN = np.sum(np.logical_and(predicted == 0, true_values == 1))
    
    # For choose = 1, the function chooses class 'adopted' as the main class
    if class_to_choose == 'adopted':
        accuracy = (TP+TN)/len(true_values)
        precision = TP/(TP+FP)
        recall = TP/(TP+FN)
        f1 = 1/(0.5*(1/precision+1/recall))
    else:
        '''
        For else, the function chooses class 'not adopted' as the main class
        by taking the the True Negative as the value for calculating
        accuracy, precision, recall, f1 score
        '''
        accuracy = (TN+TP)/len(true_values)
        precision = TN/(TN+FN)
        recall = TN/(TN+FP)
        f1 = 1/(0.5*(1/precision+1/recall))
    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1
    
# Outputs the predictions with a specific threshold
def get_prediction(pred, threshold):
    pred_threshold = (pred > threshold).astype(int)
    return pred_threshold

def find_threshold(pred, true_values, class_to_choose):
    '''
    Creates a pandas data frame for plotting the respective values 
    with a threshold from 0 to 1. 
    Returns: 
       - for all the thresholds their accuarcy, precisions, recalls and f1 scores
    '''
    accuracies = []
    precisions = []
    recalls = []
    f1_scores = []
    for i in np.linspace(0, 1, 41):
        predictions = get_prediction(pred, i)
        accu_, prec_, rec_, f1_= build_confusion_matrix(predictions, true_values, class_to_choose)
        accuracies.append(accu_)
        precisions.append(prec_)
        recalls.append(rec_)
        f1_scores.append(f1_)
        
    df_data = pd.DataFrame(dict(x = np.linspace(0, 1, 41), 
                                Accuracy = accuracies, 
                                Precision = precisions, 
                                Recall = recalls, 
                                F1_Score = f1_scores))
    return df_data

Save dogs!¶

Let's compare compare the different metrics:

Accuracy*

Accuracy shows the percentags of dogs being adopted and not adopted. We don't know have if we many true positive or true negative, since it's just a sum of them over the toal.

Precision

Precisions shows percentags how many dogs predicted as adopted were correctly adopted and dogs which were adopted and we predicted them as not adopted, thus we might want to maximize this.

Recall

Recalls gives you what fractions of dogs which were adopted were correctly predicted. We might want to also maximize this.

F1_Score

Since F1 uses harmonic mean between precision and recall. As we want to maximize those two, we decided to find the threshold based on the F1 Score.

We want to use the adopted class for for maximizing the F1_Score, as we want to look at the adoptions we predicted as true, and the respective precision and recall.

def build_k_indices(y, k_fold, seed):
    """
    Function that builds k random indices from the length of the
    dataset for the cross validation
    Returns
       - random indeces from our dataset
    """
    num_row = y.shape[0]
    interval = int(num_row / k_fold)
    np.random.seed(seed)
    indices = np.random.permutation(num_row)
    k_indices = [indices[k * interval: (k + 1) * interval]
                 for k in range(k_fold)]
    
    return np.array(k_indices)

def cross_validation(y, x, k_indices, k, learn=1, estim=1, depth=1, choose = 1):
    '''
    Does the k-fold (5) split on the dataset and performs cross validation
    '''
    te_indice = k_indices[k]
    tr_indice = k_indices[~(np.arange(k_indices.shape[0]) == k)]
    tr_indice = tr_indice.reshape(-1)
    y_te_c = y[te_indice]
    y_tr_c = y[tr_indice]
    x_te_c = x[te_indice]
    x_tr_c = x[tr_indice]
    
    # Standartize both the datasets
    st_x_tr = standardize(x_tr_c)
    st_x_te = standardize(x_te_c)
    
    # local variable learn defines the type of models for training
    if learn == 1:
        logistic = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs').fit(st_x_tr,
                                                          y_tr_c)
        pred = logistic.predict_proba(st_x_te)[:,1]
        # 'choose' chooses the class with which accuracy, precision,
        # recall and f1_score is calculated
        if choose == 1:
            accu, prec, rec, f1 = build_confusion_matrix(get_prediction(pred, 0.5),y_te_c)
        else:
            accu, prec, rec, f1 = build_confusion_matrix(get_prediction(pred, 0.5),y_te_c, class_to_choose = 'non-adoted')
    else:
        forest = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=estim,
                                        max_depth=depth).fit(st_x_tr, 
                                                            y_tr_c)
        pred = forest.predict(st_x_te)
        if choose == 1:
            accu, prec, rec, f1= build_confusion_matrix(pred, y_te_c)
        else:
            accu, prec, rec, f1= build_confusion_matrix(pred, y_te_c, class_to_choose = 'non-adpoted')
    return accu, prec, rec, f1

# Performs the cross validation testing on the data   
def cross_val_test(y, x, learn = 1, estim=1, depth=1, choose = "adopted", f1 = 1):
    seed = 1
    k_fold = 5
    k_indices = build_k_indices(y, k_fold, seed)
    f1_full = []
    accu_full = []
    prec_full = []
    rec_full = []
    for i in range(k_fold):
        accu, prec, rec, f1 = cross_validation(y, x, k_indices, i, learn, estim=estim, 
                                               depth=depth, choose = choose)
        f1_full.append(f1)
        accu_full.append(accu)
        prec_full.append(prec)
        rec_full.append(rec)
    return f1_full, accu_full, prec_full, rec_full

# A function that runs a greedy algortihm that iteratively removes
# features from the dataset 
def greedy_search(y, x, features):
    worst_list = []
    while len(features) >= 1:
        best = 0
        index = 0
        for i in range(len(features)):
            deleted = np.delete(x, i, axis = 1)
            accu_real, prec_real, rec_real, f1_alll = cross_val_test(y, deleted)
            #print(f1)
            if f1 > best:
                best = f1
                best_delete = features[i]
                index = i
        x = np.delete(x, index, axis = 1)
        worst = features.pop(index)
        worst_list.append(worst)
        print('Worst feature out of {} is the: '.format(len(features)), best_delete)
        print('F1 score with taking out the', best_delete,'is {}'.format(best))
    return worst_list

We created a function for greedily iterating over all the features, by maximizing the F1_score, and deleting the feature without which we have the highest F1 score. But as an online method of removing the features is time expensive, we decided to implement an offline method for removing the features, by using Chi-squared independence test, to greedily remove the worst features.

By visualizing the f1 scores in boxplots, we see that the best amount of features is 25, which makes sense for us, as by removing too many features we cannot make a reasonable prediction on our preferred class. And with too many features our model become too complex and overfits the data

def grid_cross_val(y, x, class_to_choose = 1):
    '''
        This functions does grid watch for a predefined range of values. 
        It only keeps the best outcome measure for that value. 
        
        returns: a list of metrics for the best estimator and depth
    '''
    accuracy = 0
    precision = 0
    recall = 0
    f1_score = 0

    best_estimator = 0
    best_depth = 0
    best_f1_score = 0
    
    for estimator in np.linspace(start=80, stop=120, num=8).astype(int):
        for depth in np.linspace(start=6, stop=20, num=8).astype(int):
            if class_to_choose == "adopted":
                accu_, prec_, rec_, f1_ = cross_val_test(y, x, 2, estimator, depth)
            else:
                accu_, prec_, rec_, f1_ = cross_val_test(y, x, 2, estimator, depth, class_to_choose)
                
            mean_f1_score = np.mean(f1_, axis=0)
            if mean_f1_score > best_f1_score:
                best_f1_score = mean_f1_score
                accuracy = accu_
                precision = prec_
                recall  =  rec_
                f1_score = f1_
                best_estimator = estimator
                best_depth = depth

    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score, best_depth, best_estimator
